**Clinical Reasoning:**
The infant has isolated mucosal bleeding (epistaxis), purpura, petechiae, and mild thrombocytopenia despite markedly elevated platelet counts—suggestive of impaired platelet function rather than quantitative defects. Platelet aggregation with ristocetin is normal, ruling out Glanzmann's thrombasthenia. Normal PT/aPTT suggests intact intrinsic and extrinsic pathways, excluding classic inherited von Willebrand disease (VWD) only if there were prolonged times—but here, aPTT is mildly prolonged but still within acceptable range. However, the combination of epistaxis, easy bruising, and petechiae in a young infant with normal coagulation tests points strongly toward von Willebrand disease because VWD often presents with variable bleeding tendencies and can show normal PT/aPTT even though it affects Factor VIII and vWF binding. Large platelets seen on smear support VWD since they're commonly observed in this condition.

